In this article, Soledad O'Brien takes readers inside a jail in Miami where many mentally ill inmates are housed on the "forgotten floor" until they are ready to appear in court. President Bush underwent a colonoscopy procedure on Saturday at the National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Maryland. Five small polyps were removed from his colon, none of which appeared worrisome. The polyps were sent to the National Naval Medical Center for routine microscopic examination, and results are expected in two to three days. The procedure was supervised by Dr. Richard Tubb, Bush's physician, and conducted by a multidisciplinary team from the National Naval Medical Center. The president is in good humor and will resume his activities at Camp David. Vice President Dick Cheney assumed presidential power during the procedure, but no official action was required before Bush reclaimed presidential power. The American Cancer Society recommends that people without high risk factors or symptoms begin getting screened for signs of colorectal cancer at age 50.

The charge is punishable by up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine. Vick also admitted to buying pit bulls and the property used for training and fighting the dogs, but he did not bet on the fights or receive any of the money won. Vick agreed to cooperate with investigators and provide all information he may have on any criminal activity, and to testify if necessary. Prosecutors have asked for permission to euthanize the dogs involved in the case, but the dogs could serve as important evidence in the cases against Vick and his co-conspirators. NFL Commissioner Roger Goodell said he would review the status of the suspension after the legal proceedings are over.

The wildfires in Southern California have caused significant destruction and loss of life, with 500 homes lost in the mountainous region of San Bernardino County and 1,664 structures destroyed overall, including 1,436 homes. The fires have killed three people and injured 40, and have burned over 434,543 acres, or about 10 times the size of Washington, D.C. The FBI and the Orange County Fire Authority are investigating the Santiago fire, which has burned over 19,000 acres and is suspected to be an arson. A Sudanese court has found a British teacher, Gillian Gibbons, guilty of insulting religion after she allowed her students to name a teddy bear "Mohammed." Gibbons was sentenced to 15 days in prison and faces deportation after her sentence is served. The teacher was arrested on Sunday and faced charges under Article 125 of Sudan's constitution, which relates to insulting religion and inciting hatred. The British Foreign Office has expressed its dissatisfaction with the verdict and is providing consular assistance to Gibbons. The teacher's lawyer plans to appeal the verdict.

Seven college students died in a weekend fire at a beach house in Ocean Isle Beach, North Carolina. The fire occurred early Sunday morning and engulfed the house in flames, leaving little more than the framing intact. The victims were identified as six University of South Carolina students and a Clemson University student. Six other South Carolina students were able to escape the house in time, but one of them, Chip Auman's 18-year-old daughter, was hospitalized due to smoke inhalation complications. The cause of the fire is still under investigation, but authorities do not believe foul play was involved. The university community is offering support and counseling to students affected by the tragedy.

Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez has cut all ties with Colombia as long as current Colombian President Alvaro Uribe is in office. Chavez had been mediating efforts to secure the release of hostages held by the FARC and ELN guerrilla groups, but Uribe ended Chavez's participation without notice, citing protocol violations. Chavez accused Uribe of lying and bowing to pressure from Washington to "get rid of Chavez." Despite this, Chavez expressed his willingness to help the Colombian people.

Ann Curley, a type I diabetic, shares her personal story of living with diabetes for 40 years. She recounts how she was diagnosed at the age of 7 by Dr. Robert Deputy, who taught her how to test her urine for sugar, give herself injections of insulin, and follow a diabetic diet. Despite the challenges, Curley views her diagnosis as a blessing in disguise, as it forced her family to eat healthily and taught her about good nutrition. She also discusses the advancements in diabetes technology, including home blood glucose testing kits, insulin pumps, and continuous glucose monitors. Curley participated in clinical trials for three different CGM devices and found them all to be accurate. She hopes to live another 40 years and is grateful for the progress made in diabetes technology.

Former Wales and British Lions center Ray Gravell has passed away at the age of 56 due to a suspected heart attack. Gravell won 23 caps for Wales and played on the Lions tour of South Africa in 1980. He made his debut for Wales in 1975 and was known for his passion, flair, and dignity on the field. After retiring as a player in 1985, Gravell became president of Llanelli RFC and the Llanelli Scarlets, and also pursued a career as an actor and rugby broadcaster. Earlier this year, Gravell had his right leg amputated below the knee due to complications linked with his diabetes, but he had been recovering well. The Welsh Rugby Union (WRU) has praised Gravell as an ambassador for rugby and Wales, and a great example of how the game can bring out the best in a person.

Barack Obama's presidential campaign is facing controversy after it was revealed that one of the performers at an upcoming gospel concert in South Carolina, Donnie McClurkin, has made statements against the LGBTQ+ community. McClurkin has said that homosexuality is a choice and that he was "once involved with those desires and those thoughts" but was able to overcome them through prayer. Atletico Madrid defeated Real Zaragoza 4-0 in the Spanish Primera Liga, with Luis Garcia scoring his first goal for the club and Diego Forlan, Maxi Rodriguez, and Kepa also finding the back of the net. Getafe won their first game of the season, defeating Murcia 2-0 with goals from Kepa and Francisco Casero. Las Vegas Sands Corp. is a company that owns several properties in Las Vegas and Macau, including The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino and the Sands Expo and Convention Center in Las Vegas, and the Sands Macau in Macau. The Venetian Casino Resort opened in 1999 and has since received recognition for revolutionizing the hotel industry in Las Vegas. The property has 3,014 suites, 18 restaurants, and a retail mall with canals and gondolas. The US Secretary of State, Condoleezza Rice, has announced that State Department officials should serve where they are needed, including in war-torn Iraq. At least seven deaths have been attributed to the wildfires in Southern California, including four bodies found in a canyon east of San Diego. Over 9,000 firefighters are battling the blazes, which have scorched 472,478 acres (738 square miles) of land, an area roughly three-quarters of the size of Rhode Island. The cost of homes destroyed by the wildfires is likely to top $1 billion in San Diego County alone. Federal help has been promised to those affected by the fires, and evacuations have been ordered in several communities. Arson investigations are under way in connection with some of the wildfires.

The commander of the USS Hampton, Cmdr. Michael B. Portland, has been relieved of his command due to a loss of confidence in his ability to lead the crew. This decision comes after an investigation into misconduct by crew members, including falsifying inspection records for the cooling system of the ship's nuclear reactor. Six personnel have been punished for their actions, and one officer and two enlisted crew members have been temporarily reassigned to Submarine Squadron 11. The misconduct was discovered on September 17, and a fact-finding investigation is ongoing. The USS Hampton remains in port in San Diego, California, with a crew of 13 officers and 116 enlisted personnel.

A bus crashed into a pickup truck and an 18-wheeler on a highway in Arkansas, killing the pickup driver and two bus riders. Forty people were injured in the crash, which shut down a 13-mile stretch of Interstate-40. The bus was traveling from Chicago to Dallas when the accident occurred. The driver of the bus and the driver of the 18-wheeler suffered minor injuries, while two passengers were found dead inside the bus. The names of the deceased have not been released.

Kelly Pless, a 31-year-old graduate student from Sunny Isles Beach, Florida, struggled with her weight for most of her adult life. She reached her breaking point when she had trouble breathing and doctors told her that her weight was to blame. Despite her doubts, Pless decided to take action and started walking and running to lose weight. She adopted an "eat to live" philosophy and focused on portion control and satisfying her cravings with fruit. Pless has lost 95 pounds and kept it off for 1½ years, and has set a new professional goal to pursue a doctorate in food and exercise psychology to help others who are battling obesity and eating disorders. Running has become a constant for Pless and has done more for her than maintain her weight, which is now about 125 pounds.

The Singapore Airlines A380, the world's largest commercial jet, made its maiden passenger journey between Singapore and Sydney this week, two years late and billions of dollars over budget. The aircraft features "beyond first class" cabins with private suites, double beds, and luxury amenities. The airline has ordered 19 superjumbos and will begin scheduled service between Singapore and Sydney next month, with plans to expand to London's Heathrow Airport in 2008. The A380's delivery schedule is ambitious, with 13 deliveries planned for 2008, 25 in 2009, and 45 in 2010. The aircraft has a wingspan of 79.8 meters, length of 73 meters, and height of 24.1 meters, with a internal cabin width of 6.58 meters and seating capacity of 555. The A380's flight range is 15,000 kilometers, and it features 500 kilometers of wiring. The airline has received high demand for tickets, with the top ticket price selling for US$100,380, with economy seats available for US$560.

The illegal export of US military technology to Iran and China is a growing concern, according to the Justice Department. Tens of thousands of Congolese refugees fled camps in the Democratic Republic of Congo on Tuesday as rebel troops attacked government forces in the area. Genarlow Wilson, a 21-year-old man who was released from prison last week after serving two years of a 10-year sentence for aggravated child molestation, rejected a plea deal from prosecutors despite it potentially releasing him from prison months earlier. The confirmation of Michael Mukasey as Attorney General is likely, despite concerns from some Democratic senators about his views on "waterboarding" and the president's power to order electronic surveillance. 1. The Hamburger: Louis' Lunch in New Haven, Connecticut is credited as the birthplace of the hamburger, with the story going that a rushed businessman asked owner Louis Lassen for something quick to eat on the run, and Lassen cooked up a beef patty and served it between bread.
2. The Fried Twinkie: At The ChipShop in Brooklyn, New York, owner Christopher Sell invented the fried Twinkie by freezing the snack, dipping it in batter, and deep-frying it.
3. Root Beer Float: In 1893, a failed gold-miner-turned-soda-company-owner named Frank J. Wisner was drinking a bottle of his Myers Avenue Red root beer while looking up at Cow Mountain in Colorado, and he had the idea to float a scoop of vanilla ice cream in the root beer.
4. Corn Dogs: Ed Waldmire, Jr. invented the corn dog in 1946, debuting the Cozy Dog -- the first corn dog on a stick -- at his Cozy Dog Drive In in Springfield, Illinois.
5. The Pizzeria: Gennaro Lombardi opened the first true pizzeria in New York City in 1905, with his employee Anthony "Totonno" Pero selling pizzas out of the back of the store.
6. Fat Darrell: At R.U. Hungry in New Brunswick, New Jersey, a student named Darrell W. Butler invented the Fat Darrell by adding chicken fingers, mozzarella sticks, French fries, and marinara sauce to a sandwich.
7. Philly Cheesesteak: Pat's King Of Steaks in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania is credited as the birthplace of the Philly cheesesteak, with the story going that hot dog stand owners Pasquale and Harry Olivieri added onions to a steak sandwich in 1932.
8. Onion Rings: According to Pig Stand in Dallas, Texas, a careless cook accidentally dropped an onion slice in batter and pulled it out and tossed it in the fryer, inventing the onion ring.
9. Derby Pie: The Kern family of Melrose Inn in Prospect, Kentucky invented derby pie, a chocolate and pecan tart with a pastry-dough crust, with the recipe jealously guarded by the family.

Authorities in Azerbaijan have uncovered a terror plot against the US Embassy in the capital city of Baku, prompting the embassy to close its doors to the public. A North Korean freighter was hijacked by pirates off the coast of Somalia, but the crew was able to regain control of the ship after a deadly battle. The USS James E. Lee Boyd Malvo, the sniper who terrorized the Washington area in 2002, is still grappling with shame, guilt, and remorse according to a letter he wrote to CNN. Russian President Vladimir Putin visited Tehran, Iran on Tuesday, where he met with Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad and other leaders of Caspian Sea nations. Three French journalists were released from custody in Chad, hours after French President Nicolas Sarkozy held emergency talks with Chadian President Idriss Deby. Donohue, said that the abuse occurred before the girl was 3 years old and that the mother is cooperating with investigators. The suspect, Chester Arthur Stiles, is being sought by the FBI on state charges of sexual assault and lewdness with a minor under the age of 14. A man who found the tape in the desert and held onto it for five months before turning it over to authorities is facing charges of exhibiting pornography and possession of child pornography.

Sen. Barack Obama criticized Sen. Hillary Clinton's recent vote to declare Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps a foreign terrorist group, saying it was a "blank check" for President Bush to take military action against Iran. Obama argued that Clinton's vote showed flawed judgment, as she had also supported the resolution to authorize force in Ira in 2002. Clinton defended her vote, saying it was a nonbinding resolution and that sanctions would be imposed to send a message to Iran's leadership. Obama also said he would step up efforts to clarify his differences with Clinton and suggested that he could better unite the country and offer "something new" as president.

Charges against Bryant Purvis, one of the six black students accused of beating a white student in Jena, Louisiana, were reduced to second-degree aggravated battery during his arraignment. Purvis entered a not guilty plea to the reduced charges and is focusing on his studies and basketball. Charges have been reduced against at least five of the students in the racially charged "Jena 6" case, with the exception of Mychal Bell, who is still in jail due to a probation violation.

Up to 1,000 human rights campaigners demonstrated in front of No. 10 Downing Street in London, calling on the British government to demand that full democracy be restored in Pakistan. The protesters carried placards and chanted in support of the resignation of Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf, who imposed a state of emergency in the country a week ago. The demonstration was led by Jemima Khan, the ex-wife of former Pakistani cricket star Imran Khan, who has been under house arrest since the emergency declaration. The protesters delivered a petition to a doorman at Downing Street, calling on Britain to use its influence to ensure that all institutions are in place well in advance of Pakistani elections originally scheduled for early next year. The petition also demands that Pakistan restore democracy and the judiciary and calls on Musharraf to release all political prisoners, including lawyers, journalists, and opposition politicians.

Rapper T.I. was arrested in Atlanta on Saturday on federal gun charges after his bodyguard-turned-informant delivered three machine guns and two silencers to the hip-hop star, according to the Justice Department. T.I., whose real name is Clifford Harris, was taken into custody without incident and is expected to appear in court on Friday for a bond hearing. The 27-year-old entertainer was convicted on felony drug charges in 1998 and is not allowed to own guns due to his criminal record. Authorities found six other guns, five of them loaded, in his bedroom closet during a search of his home. The arrest came after the bodyguard, who has worked for Harris since July, was arrested purchasing the guns and agreed to cooperate with the ATF. The guns were not registered on the National Firearms Registration and Transfer Record as required by law.

Three Chinese nationals have been arrested in the US for importing and selling counterfeit luxury handbags and wallets worth millions of dollars. The operation is believed to be one of the largest counterfeit schemes ever discovered, with over 300,000 fake items sold to unsuspecting customers. The alleged leaders of the operation are three Chinese citizens living in New York, who were arrested after a five-year investigation by Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents. The charges were unsealed when the defendants were taken into custody, and authorities seized and froze 29 bank accounts and three properties in New York. The defendants will be arraigned in Richmond, Virginia at a later date.

Bill Proenza, the director of the National Hurricane Center (NHC), has left his position after nearly half of the center's staff signed a petition calling for his ouster. Proenza is still employed by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), but he is currently on leave. The petition was signed by 23 staff members, including four of five senior hurricane specialists, who were unhappy not only with Proenza's comments about a key hurricane satellite called QuikSCAT but also with the environment at the center. Proenza told CNN he had contacted his superiors in Washington about "ways to move forward," but he refused to resign. Proenza graduated from Florida State University with a degree in meteorology and began his career in tropical meteorology in the mid-1960s at NHC.

At least 1,723 people have died and 15,000 have been injured in Bangladesh after a devastating tropical cyclone, Cyclone Sidr, ripped through the western coast of the country. The cyclone made landfall Thursday night and unleashed floodwaters, causing widespread destruction and displacement. The government has identified the 12 worst-affected districts, all located on the southern coast, and the Bangladeshi air force, army, and navy are working to provide shelter for the many people who have been displaced. Power is still out in much of the country, but it is being restored. The U.N. World Food Programme has enough high-energy biscuits to feed 400,000 people for several days, and other humanitarian groups, such as Save the Children, are appealing for aid to assist children and families affected by the disaster. The US Department of State has pledged to work with the government and foreign donors to assist in relieving the effects of the disaster.

A man has been indicted on federal charges for allegedly displaying hangman's nooses from the back of a pickup truck during a civil rights march in Jena, Louisiana. The man, Jeremiah Munsen, 18, of Grant Parish, repeatedly drove slowly past a group of marchers gathered at a bus depot in Alexandria, Louisiana, as they awaited buses to return them to Tennessee. As many as 20,000 marchers had taken part in the huge protests in Jena, where authorities had been accused of injustice in the handling of racially charged cases, including the hanging of nooses in a tree after a group of black high school students sat in an area where traditionally only white students sat. Munsen and an unnamed conspirator had attached nooses to their pickup on September 20 and driven to Alexandria specifically to threaten and intimidate the marchers, according to the authorities. A juvenile passenger was apprehended with Munsen and admitted to tying the nooses and having "KKK" tattooed on his chest. The indictment accuses Munsen of conduct that constitutes a federal civil rights conspiracy violation and a federal hate crime.

R.E.M. debuted a new song, "Until the Day Is Done," on CNN's "Anderson Cooper 360°" program as part of the network's four-hour documentary "Planet in Peril." The song will also appear in the documentary, which focuses on environmental crises around the world. R.E.M. singer Michael Stipe said the band was honored to be involved with the project and that the group's longstanding commitment to environmental causes made them a natural choice. The documentary features CNN anchor Anderson Cooper, chief medical correspondent Dr. Sanjay Gupta, and "Animal Planet" host and wildlife biologist Jeff Corwin, and was filmed in 13 countries. "Planet in Peril" will air on October 23 and 24 at 9 p.m. ET on CNN.

The US government is planning to build a border fence along the Texas-Mexico border, but about 100 landowners are resisting the effort. Eloisa Tamez, who owns three acres of land along the border, is determined to fight the government's plan, saying she will not allow them to survey her land. The government believes the fence will help curb illegal immigration and drug trafficking, but opponents argue it is a waste of resources and will not be effective. The Department of Homeland Security has begun legal action against landowners and municipalities who have refused to give government surveyors access to their land, and the government plans to build 700 miles of fence along the border, including 370 miles by the end of this year.

Some Christian pastors in urban areas are turning to the Church of Scientology for help with social programs, despite the church's controversial reputation. The pastors, including Rev. Charles Kennedy of the Glorious Church of God in Christ in Tampa, Florida, and Rev. James McLaughlin of the Wayman Chapel African Methodist Episcopal Church in Houston, Texas, are using Scientology's social programs, such as "The Way to Happiness" and "Narconon," to address issues like crime, addiction, and poverty in their communities. While they do not worship God or Jesus Christ, they see Scientology's teachings as a tool to augment their Christian beliefs and help their communities. However, critics like Rick Ross, a court-certified Scientology expert, warn that mainstream acceptance of Scientology's programs could lead to increased recruitment and a dilution of Christian values.

A car bomb attack in Algeria has killed 3 people and injured 23, according to the Algerian Press Service. The attack occurred near an office housing judicial police in the city of Thenia, about 50 km east of the capital of Algiers. The blast destroyed about 20 houses and a commission has been appointed to help the victims. Islamic extremists in Algeria and other North African countries have carried out several attacks in recent years, including a bombing last year that killed at least 24 people and wounded over 220 in the capital of Algiers. Al Qaeda has claimed responsibility for some of these attacks.

Michael Vick, the suspended NFL quarterback, has been ordered to adhere to tightened restrictions after testing positive for marijuana use. He must participate in substance abuse therapy and mental health counseling and stay home between 10pm and 6am, electronically monitored. These conditions will apply until his sentencing on December 10. Vick faces a possible prison term of 12-18 months after pleading guilty to federal conspiracy charges related to dogfighting on his property in Virginia.

Former Beatles Paul McCartney and Ringo Starr sat down for an interview on CNN's "Larry King Live" to discuss the 40th anniversary of the band's breakup and the success of Cirque du Soleil's "Love" show, which features the Beatles' music. The pair joked and reminisced about their time in the band, with Starr saying they were "kids from Liverpool" who never expected to become a global phenomenon. McCartney added that the band's music has stood the test of time and continues to be enjoyed by new generations of fans. The widows of John Lennon and George Harrison also appeared on the show, discussing their husbands' involvement in the project and the ongoing impact of their music.

According to the article, three Palestinians, including two sick children, have died recently while waiting for resettlement from Iraq at the Al Waleed refugee camp along the Syrian border. The UNHCR has appealed for the resettlement of "vulnerable and sick" children in the camp, where about 2,000 Palestinian refugees are stranded and face difficult living conditions. Seven people, including three children, have died at the camp since refugees began arriving in March 2006. The UNHCR has helped resettle one family of eight with sick children to Norway last August and is working to identify other medical cases for resettlement. The agency has sought solutions for the whole group since last year and has received positive indications from Sudan and Chile.

A Japanese balloonist, Michio Kanda, has gone missing while flying from Japan to the west coast of the United States. He was last heard from via satellite phone at 9am Alaska time on Thursday, but missed three subsequent scheduled calls. The US Coast Guard has launched searches for him using two C130 Hercules planes and two cutters, but they are at least a day away from the area. Kanda is equipped with provisions and a survival suit, and holds the world record for the longest-duration balloon flight.

The Democratic presidential candidates, Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama, will face off in a debate on Thursday night at the Kodak Theatre in Los Angeles. The debate, sponsored by CNN, the Los Angeles Times, and Politico, will start at 8 pm ET and will be moderated by Wolf Blitzer. This is the first debate since Obama's convincing victory in South Carolina and Clinton's win in the Florida primary. The candidates will likely focus on the economy, as both have split victories in their parties' early-voting states. Obama has won in Iowa and South Carolina, while Clinton has won in New Hampshire, Nevada, Michigan, and Florida. However, the Michigan and Florida contests awarded no delegates, and all major Democratic presidential candidates have pledged to avoid campaigning in those states. Clinton has the overall lead in delegates, including superdelegates, with 232 delegates to Obama's 158. The debate may be more restrained than last week's brutal showdown, as Clinton has largely steered clear of opportunities to take aim at Obama.

A car bomb exploded near a U.S. Embassy vehicle in Beirut, Lebanon, killing at least three Lebanese bystanders and injuring 21 others, including an American citizen. The driver and passenger of the embassy vehicle were Lebanese security personnel and suffered minor injuries. The U.S. State Department condemned the attack and expressed condolences to the families of the victims. The explosion occurred during a major political crisis in Lebanon, which has been without a president for nearly eight weeks. This is the latest in a series of attacks against pro-Western, anti-Syrian targets in Beirut.

This article from Mental Floss highlights eight unusual fan stories from various sports and events. Here's a summary of each story:

1. Bobby Murcer's Biggest Fan: In 1977, Bobby Murcer, a former New York Yankee, promised a terminally ill fan named Scott Crull that he would hit a home run for him. That night, Murcer hit two home runs, but the fan passed away shortly after. The story gained national attention and highlights the emotional connection between athletes and their fans.
2. The Good Luck Charmers: The Detroit Red Wings have a strange tradition of throwing an octopus onto the ice before games, which is believed to bring good luck. The tradition started in 1952 and has continued to this day, despite objections from PETA.
3. The John 3:16 Guy: Rollen Stewart, also known as "Rainbow Man," became a fixture at major sporting events in the 1970s and 80s with his John 3:16 signs. He was a born-again Christian and brought his message to various events, including the World Series, Super Bowl, Olympics, and World Cup.
4. The All-Star Heckler: Robin Ficker was a Maryland lawyer and Washington Bullets fan who became the NBA's most prominent heckler. He would loudly disrupt games with his antics, including reading excerpts from a sex-laden autobiography by Phil Jackson.
5. Kim Jong-il: The Supreme Commander of the Korean People's Army is a hoops junkie and has a video library of every Michael Jordan game.
6. David Letterman's Stalker: Margaret Ray was a frequent trespasser on David Letterman's estate and was arrested for stealing his Porsche in 1988. She was diagnosed with schizophrenia and committed suicide in 1998.
7. Joe from Saddle River: Joe Benigno is a die-hard Jets, Mets, and Rangers fan who became a frequent caller to WFAN, New York's all-sports radio station. He won the station's Fan Appreciation Day contest in 1994 and became an overnight host in 1995.
8. Steffi Graf's Biggest Fanatic: Gunter Parche stabbed Monica Seles during a 1993 match in one of the most disturbing incidents in sports history. He was ordered to attend mandatory counseling and received a two-year suspended sentence.
